tip.text:
Sure you've been in your fair share of cafes, but not one quite like this. Owner Aidan, an avid collector and lover of all things natural history, has lovingly (and painstakingly) created a cafe-cum-miniature-natural-history-museum and it's a transportive, singular experience - as close to the cupboard-into-Narnia flex as it's possible to get. From the luxey pastel pink and creme hues; to the foraged branches and moss; to the surreal taxidermy sitting proud, it's an aesthetic rarity - and a reminder that sometimes fetishes can be a good thing.

With the layout of a small gallery, glass cabinets are filled with all manner of fossils, bones, artefacts and specimens. All for sale; all worthy of a momentary browse. And if that tummy starts to rumble, you'll find coffees, cakes and a short breakfast and lunch menu with carefully put together dishes such as Ottolenghi home-baked beans, salsa and beetroot yoghurt on sourdough; manchego and cheddar toastie with truffle oil; or slow roasted garlic and thyme mushrooms on toast. Keep an eye out for a cute garden out back too.

listing.name: The Viktor Wynd Museum of Curiosities
listing.subtitle: Surreal Oddities

tip.text:
Imagine if every object you ever found rare, magical or beautiful in any way was put inside a small and dark basement of wonder in Hackney. For us, that would include plenty of Daily Sport newspapers from the early 00s. Luckily Viktor Wynd - a collector with no real time for categorisation or labelling - has a slightly more imaginative mind and he's created an incoherent vision of the world at this surreal museum on Mare Street.

The basement is full of all sorts: from priceless marvels of the natural and scientific worlds like dodo bones to the interesting aesthetics of McDonald's Happy Meal toys; master etchings to prison inmates doodles and pretty much anything else you can imagine. There's also an art gallery upstairs which puts on different shows, normally of the surreal variety.

Entry is £5 which includes a cup of tea, and £2.50 on Thursdays between 6pm-10pm.

This is a refuge for those out there struggling with the realities of adulthood and in need of a quick fix of nostalgia. Oh hey, everyone! It's a history of toys; a smallish museum that's been amassing childhood-related objects since 1872 and displaying them as a record of how kids have been entertained since kids were allowed to have fun.

In a vast, ornate hall that feels somewhat like a train station, are all the classic toys from over the years - from puppet theatres from the 1970s, to Victorian praxinoscopes; Barbie dolls to Playstations. There isn't that much info here and it doesn't take longer than 45 minutes to take in, but it's still a welcome throwback that's probably geared more towards adults than kids themselves. If you don’t like children or being reminded that you were once a child, do not come here.

Sat rather incongruously on Whitechapel High Street is the Grade II-listed Whitechapel Gallery. It might not be as large or prestigious as the likes of the Tate, but it's nevertheless an edgy place to catch some contemporary art and spend an hour of your hard-earned time. Harking back to 1901, it's always been about art by the people, for the people - there are several rooms here with free exhibits, along with a main show which costs a few bucks.

Along with the white walls, you'll find a research centre, archive room and a pretty nice cafe to mooch about in. It's also been the launchpad for many a big name, with Jackson Pollock, Mark Rothko and Frida Kahlo all exhibiting here before they went HUGE.

If the Brunels were about today, we would follow the flip out of him on all available social channels. Fuck the Kardashians, this family really deserved the adoration - not only did Isambard Brunel design all manner of incredible bridges and tunnels (one of the most ingenious and prolific figures in engineering history), the family threw ambitious underwater banquets and wild parties whilst also building fairgrounds and shopping arcades.

This small museum details some of those projects including the iconic Thames Tunnel and is home to the Grand Entrance Hall - the world's first caisson and most popular visitor attraction in 1843. It was where the world's first underground concert happened and was the world's first underground theatre. Basically, a lot of world first's happened here. Drop by to pay your respects to a true engineering institution.

Voted ‘London’s Ugliest Building’ in a 2003 poll, it seems that we haven’t been able to trust the British public long before the Brexit vote. This concrete Ziggurat is a mecca for all Brutalist architecture lovers, playing host to classical & contemporary music concerts, theatre performances, film screenings and art exhibitions. It also houses a humongous public library and a conservatory that is nothing short of a tropical oasis. Well, this is the largest arts centre in Europe we're talking about.

Have a mooch on in and be greeted to big industrial spaces equipped with high ceilings, artificial lighting, and the odd inconspicuous chair to sit back and absorb the raw ambience. Not the usual flouncy decoration, but they let their exhibitions do the talking. If you’re under 25 be sure to sign up to their free Young Barbican membership programme, which knocks the price of their exhibitions and film screenings to £5. Don’t say we don’t look out for ya.

It might seem to you that London only began to actually exist when you started living here but it turns out,  it's been going for a while. This free museum tells the dramatic tale of London and it's been a rocky old ride. There are 9 free galleries to look at and it goes a little like this: London before London > Roman London > Medieval London > War Plague and Fire > Expanding City > People's City > World City. With over 2 million objects in their collection, they've got all sorts of bits to show here. Expect to see plenty of tourists and families.

If you've got a feeling for all things threads, head to the colourful cube in Bermondsey also known as the Fashion and Textile Museum. It happens to be the UK's only museum solely dedicated to showcasing developments in contemporary fashion - it doesn't have a permanent collection, but puts on temporary shows that cover all sorts. Well, when we say all sorts we're really talking fashion. It has a cafe, as you might expect, and entry is £9 which is a little bit steep but when in Bermondsey eh?

So, there are a lot of words going on here: Old Operating Theatre Museum. But before you go thinking it's a museum about old West End shows, just let us be the first to tell you: it's really, really not that. This is an old 'operating theatre' - i.e., a non-sterile amphitheatre where doctors would perform operations while students and whoever fancied watching someone get cut open could watch. Oh, and this was also before anaesthetic. Makes us feel all warm and fuzzy.

These days, you can nose around in the operating theatre, the oldest surviving one in Britain, and play around with some of the original furniture and equipment, or take a looksy at some gruesome pathological specimens. There are occasional reenactments, too, if you're into that.

Adults - £6.50; concessions - £5; under 16s - £3.50.

As frequent visitors to the Wellcome Collection, we’re plenty hyped to see another free science-orientated exhibition space opening up. Science Gallery London's ambition is to connect art, science and health through a range of stimulating, topical and innovative shows. There's no permanent collection here; instead there'll be three seasons each year that focus on something different. The space itself will also be capable of various flexes: from events, to performances, to live experiments, discussions and festivals. All focused on science - and who doesn't like science? You'd have to be a monster.

A stunning piece of modernist industrial architecture on the outside, and the embodiment of the ubiquitous white-walled gallery space on the in, White Cube is as good a place as any to catch some of that contemporary stuff in the Big Smoke.

The original White Cube Gallery gained a reputation in the 90s by giving one person shows to many of the rising YBAs, its name growing alongside those of Tracey Emin and Damien Hirst. Today it continues to host a range of conceptual, boundary-pushing shows across its two London galleries. The Bermondsey branch is the perfect size for an afternoon mooch: it's got three decent spaces, but it's not so big that you feel rushed or knackered by the end. It's also free, which is our favourite price for art (and most things for that matter).

The Tate Modern is the queen bee of the UK’s modern art scene. Housed in the former Bankside Power Station, this iconic institution has Picasso, Rothko, Pollock, Warhol, Dali & Matisse all under one roof (and free of charge). Mosey on in and be met by the sheer vastness of the Turbine Hall, a gigantic space that runs the length of the entire building. Try not to be overwhelmed - the Tate Modern is a serious feat and one needs to remain level-headed.

The gallery has numerous free collections, all organised by themes rather than chronological order. There's also 2 major temporary exhibitions that are ticketed (but usually worth the dollar). When staring at modern art trying to be profound and shiz gets a bit tiresome, the view from the top floor of the Switch House is first-class. Expect London’s skyline in all its glory (and a little bit of noseying into the living rooms of the rich & soulless).

Housed in what used to be an ice warehouse (you can still see the ice pit), this wee museum has a good collection of artefacts and tit bits about the London waterways. You can learn all about the horses that pulled the boats along the towpath and especially juicy stories of the boat people's salacious lives in Victorian society. There are even free audioguides to download on your phone. If you're real organised you can also listen to one as you walk up to the museum, along the canal, from either Paddington or Camden station. In the summer there's plenty a canal cruise and children's activity to be had too.

Entry is £3.00

If the devil makes work for idle hands, then this surreal world of home-made arcade games must be what hell looks like. Tim Hunkin, engineer extraordinaire and lover of eccentric British humour, got hooked on making his own retro games. A rare addiction and one only soothed by the turning of a space in Holborn into a retro, satirical ode to the arcades normally seen at the British seaside. Here an imagination run wild meets excellent engineering and yeah, it's a novel place to visit.

The games all follow some strange bent on reality - from the self-explanatory Autofrisk, to the regulator-evasion game of Money Laundering; a Nobel prize pinball machine to an expert that determines whether an object is art or not. It's as weird and confusing as it sounds, and the only way to really understand it is to bop in here, get some tokens, follow the instructions and expose yourself to something very different to the norm.

This small gallery - which looks bigger on the outside than it turns out to be - is about all things illustration and graphic art. Set up by Quentin Blake, most famous for sprucing up Roald Dahl's tales, its a highly-curated display of bits from illustrators past and present, who knew their way around a pen/pencil and weren't afraid to show it.

There always tends to be displays on two artists at any one time and shows cover all sorts - from adverts to animation, picture books to political cartoons and scientific drawings to fashion design. The entry fee is a little steep for the size of the place so perhaps one for when you've got a specific interest in what's on show rather than an unfocused wander about.

Left exactly as it was when he died, the house of 19th century architect John Soane is a three-house-wide labyrinth of curiosities. On display are an incredible array of famous artworks, sculptures, furniture and artefacts. If you have limited time be sure to check out the sarcophagus of the Egyptian king and the picture room in which the famous painted series 'The Rake's Progress' by William Hogarth hangs. But don't come with limited time - everything is worth swooning over for quite a while. Plus it's all free, bro.

So apparently, back in the day, people were just leavin' their babies on the sidewalk. You can't do that anymore (blame the PC police), but this museum explores the fascinating history of abandoned children, or 'foundlings'. The museum site was once a hospital for the lost bebs, and it's a gorgeous space, featuring opulent interiors and a fine collection of art. Poignant artefacts in their collection tell stories of family separation, social stigma, wartime heroism, and the search for birth mothers.

Originally the site of a Tudor palace commission by the Duke of Somerset (hence the name), the building now on this stretch of the Strand was built in 1775 and has had all sorts of occupants since then. We might be biased, but honestly, we think the current era is the best version it’s ever been. It's now host to a stellar permanent art collection; a consistent slew of good temporary affairs centred around art, design and architecture; and more recently, a series of decent nights out from the more left-field end of the musical spectrum.

It's not all high brow entertainment though - they also have a massive pop up screen in the summer showing a range of crowd pleasers; and a pop up ice rink in the winter that you will have surely seen all over the social medias.

Here we have both a world-renowned joint for contemporary art and a landmark of brutalist architecture. Part of the Southbank Centre, Hayward Gallery is composed of a sprawling and incoherent combobulation of concrete blocks that somehow adds up to make an art gallery.

After a big refurb that took a couple of years, it’s now a mighty impressive setting of polished concrete, imposing staircases, huge white walls and that endearing ruggedness that we all dig now brutalism is firmly in vogue. The exhibitions, featuring many a major contemporary artist, will cost you but are normally worth the outlay with some strong curation.

Given the sheer number of artists mooching about New Cross (estimated at 3 out of 4 people), it's about time it had an impressive, large space to present the ideas of some leading and emerging artists. Step up Goldsmiths CCA - a huge new public art gallery showing some of that good, hard-hitting, poignant contemporary stuff within its walls. The space itself is the former boiler house and laundry rooms of a Victorian bath house and the renovation, done by the Assemble team, is quite something to behold.

Across 8 gallery spaces you're getting free exhibitions (curated by the excellent Natasha Hoare), talks, performances, films and the rest of it. An intriguing architectural gem to get the mind whirring and a well overdue major art hub in the South East.
